up|29|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Someone asked me a question about opening a weak-2 bid with a 4-card major. Although there are many players who will not open a weak 2 with an outside 4 card major I completely disagree. Preempts are very powerful weapons and should be used whenever possible.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Odds are very much that with a weak hand and a 6-card suit, your best contract will be in your long suit. You might occasionally miss a 4-4 major which is not a big loss.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you pass, the opponents get a chance to enter the auction and you give them a big advantage to which they should not be entitled.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Also,  another Kib asked me, is there a minimum honor holding for a preempt. Personally I will open a weak 2 even with a weak 6 card suit. 6-card suits are powerful even if weak because you will normally have an 8 or 9 card fit and will often take at least 4 tricks in your suit even if it is weak.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On the other hand, others prefer to have some honors. Actually the ideal holding for a suit in which you preempt is QJ10 because you have some protection against losing too many tricks but you have no offense.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


