nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Although that can be right on occasion most of the time it is wrong. There is a bridge saying "^*BThe 5 level belongs to the opponents^*N" meaning it is usually wrong to bid 5 over 5. But this hand was slightly different because from West's perspective the opponents were at the 4 level. |
PG| ***** 83 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So if West bid 5@H he would be bidding ^*B5 over 4^*N. That is a much more difficult decision. With 5-5 I would tend to bid that. However, the spades holding is a red flag as at least 2 spade losers are quite possible. Had West had a singleton spade, I would choose 5 hearts but with a doubleton, I think pass was best.|
PG| ***** 84 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Another issue which I did not address during the bidding is whether East should double. The answer is yes. If partner opens, as a general rule, you can count on him for 2 tricks. So with 2 aces, East has 2 likely tricks and therefore, it is likely North is going down. Therefore, double by East would be a reasonable choice.|
PG| ***** 85 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|All of this discussion is just general principles because when you get to competitive auctions with distributional hands, you never know for sure what is going to be correct. |
PG| ***** 86 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, if you rely on the principles I just discussed (5 level belongs to the opponent, opener has 2 defensive tricks) you will make the correct decision more often than not.|
PG| ***** 87 ***** |


